If you don't have a toaster, heat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7 for the naans.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Cut the @tomato{1%medium}(cut into 2cm chunks). Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%can} in a #sieve{}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large saucepan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the @pasanda style seasoning{2}, @garam masala{1/2}, lime zest and garlic. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200}, lentils, @vegetable stock paste{15} and @water for the sauce{200} until combined.

Bring the curry to the boil, then reduce the heat to low and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Stir through the tomato and @baby spinach{40} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

== Buttery Naans ==

Once the veg has been added to the curry, cut the @plain naans{2} in half widthways, then put in your #toaster{} until golden.

If you're using the oven, put the naans onto a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle with a little @water{} and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once warmed, generously spread the @butter{10} over the naans.

== Finishing the Curry ==

Once the curry has thickened slightly, stir through the @mango chutney{40} and a squeeze of lime juice.

Season to taste with @salt{}, @pepper{} and more lime juice if needed. Remove from the heat.

Share the lentil curry between your #bowls{}.

Serve with the buttery naans alongside.

Enjoy!